<h2>Emerging Standards</h2>

<h3>Unicode MessageFormat 2.0</h3>

<p><strong>Status:</strong> Approved as part of Unicode Technical Standard #35 (CLDR) Part 9, published 2024.</p>

<p>This is the most significant development for i18n. It provides a standard message formatting syntax to replace ICU MessageFormat 1.0:</p>

<pre><code>// Variable interpolation
{Hello {$name}!}

// Plural selection
.match {$count :integer}
  1   {{You have one item}}
  *   {{You have {$count} items}}

// Date formatting
{Your appointment is {$date :datetime dateStyle=long}}

// Custom functions (extensible registry)
{$amount :currency currency=USD}</code></pre>

<p>Key improvements: consistent data model, better error handling (partial output on errors), extensible function registry, simpler nesting.</p>

<h3>TC39 Intl.MessageFormat Proposal</h3>

<p><strong>Status:</strong> Stage 1 (as of early 2025). Would bring MF2 to browsers natively:</p>

<pre><code>const mf = new Intl.MessageFormat('{Hello {$name}!}', 'en');
mf.format({ name: 'World' }); // "Hello World!"</code></pre>

<p><strong>Timeline concern:</strong> Stage 1 proposals can take 3&ndash;7 years to ship in all browsers. A polyfill/library will be necessary for the foreseeable future.</p>

<h3>Temporal API</h3>

<p><strong>Status:</strong> TC39 Stage 3 (2025). Improves timezone-aware, calendar-system-aware date handling. Integrates with <code>Intl.DateTimeFormat</code>. Does not address translation itself.</p>


<h2>Build-Time vs Runtime Translation</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Approach</th><th>Libraries</th><th>Pros</th><th>Cons</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Compile-time (per-locale build)</strong></td>
      <td>@angular/localize, @lit/localize transform</td>
      <td>Zero runtime overhead, smallest bundle</td>
      <td>No dynamic switching, CI build per locale</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Compile-time (tree-shakeable functions)</strong></td>
      <td>Paraglide, LinguiJS macro</td>
      <td>Tiny runtime (~0&ndash;2KB), type-safe, dead message elimination</td>
      <td>Build tooling required</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Runtime (eager)</strong></td>
      <td>vue-i18n, react-intl, ember-intl</td>
      <td>Dynamic switching, simple setup</td>
      <td>Larger bundle (8&ndash;16KB), runtime parsing cost</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Runtime (lazy)</strong></td>
      <td>i18next, Transloco, svelte-i18n</td>
      <td>Dynamic switching, code-split translations</td>
      <td>Network waterfall, loading states needed</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Hybrid</strong></td>
      <td>@lit/localize (both modes)</td>
      <td>Choose per deployment</td>
      <td>Two modes to maintain</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h3>Mapping to Web Everything</h3>

<p>The plugged/unplugged architecture maps naturally:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Unplugged (compile-time)</strong>: Import message functions directly. Tree-shakeable. Type-safe. No runtime overhead. Locale switching via dynamic <code>import()</code>.</li>
  <li><strong>Plugged (runtime)</strong>: Bootstrap registers a global translation context. <code>@t.key</code> resolves reactively. Dynamic locale switching via store.</li>
</ul>

<p>The message function signature is the common interface either way:</p>
<pre><code>type MessageFn = (params?: Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;) =&gt; string;</code></pre>


<h2>Web Component i18n Challenges</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Challenge</th><th>Description</th><th>Lit's Solution</th><th>Web Everything Approach</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Shadow DOM text</strong></td>
      <td>Internal strings inaccessible from outside</td>
      <td><code>msg()</code> in render method</td>
      <td><code>@t.key</code> in template expressions</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Slotted content</strong></td>
      <td>Light DOM content needs translation too</td>
      <td>Consumer translates their own slot content</td>
      <td>Same &mdash; slot content is the consumer's responsibility</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Component library strings</strong></td>
      <td>Labels like "Close", "Next" baked into components</td>
      <td><code>msg()</code> with extraction</td>
      <td>Provide translations via injector context; components read from <code>@t</code></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Locale propagation</strong></td>
      <td>How does a component know the locale changed?</td>
      <td><code>lit-localize-status</code> event + <code>@localized</code> decorator</td>
      <td>Reactive store via injector. Store change triggers re-render.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>SSR with i18n</strong></td>
      <td>Server must know locale before rendering</td>
      <td>Lit SSR supports locale</td>
      <td>Translation functions are sync; locale determined before render</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>


<h2>Proposed Architecture for Web Everything</h2>

<p>Given the existing primitives (injectors, contexts, stores, expression parsers), i18n maps cleanly:</p>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Concern</th><th>Maps To</th><th>Mechanism</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Locale state</td><td><code>CustomStore</code></td><td>Reactive, observable locale value</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Translation provision</td><td>Injector context (<code>@t</code>)</td><td>Scoped per DOM subtree</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Message formatting</td><td>Block (MessageFormatter)</td><td>MF2-based, provided via injector</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Locale detection</td><td>Pluggable strategies</td><td>Like prefetch strategies in the router</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Locale routing</td><td>Router block integration</td><td>URL parameter &rarr; locale store</td></tr>
    <tr><td>RTL switching</td><td>Behavior block</td><td>Observes <code>dir</code> attribute</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Lazy loading</td><td>Translation loader via injector</td><td>Like route loaders</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Locale change notification</td><td>Store subscription</td><td>Like any other reactive state</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<p>The <code>@t</code> context already referenced in <code>blocks.json</code> (handler expression parser's context access patterns) is the right surface API:</p>

<pre><code>&lt;span&gt;@t.greeting&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span&gt;@t.itemCount({ count: $store.items.length })&lt;/span&gt;</code></pre>


<h2>Key Design Decisions</h2>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Message syntax</strong>: MessageFormat 2.0 (recommended &mdash; forward-compatible with <code>Intl.MessageFormat</code>) vs ICU MessageFormat 1.0 (wider current tooling) vs custom (not recommended)</li>
  <li><strong>Runtime vs compile-time</strong>: Offer both via plugged/unplugged? @lit/localize proves the dual-mode approach works.</li>
  <li><strong>Translation file format</strong>: XLIFF for external exchange, JSON for development, compiled JS for runtime. Build tool converts between them.</li>
  <li><strong>Scope of blocks</strong>:
    <ul>
      <li><code>LocaleStore</code> &mdash; state management for current locale</li>
      <li><code>MessageFormatter</code> &mdash; message formatting engine (MF2)</li>
      <li><code>TranslationLoader</code> &mdash; async loading of translation files</li>
      <li><code>LocaleDetector</code> &mdash; detection strategies</li>
      <li><code>LocaleProvider</code> &mdash; custom element or behavior that sets up the injector context</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Integration with <code>@t</code></strong>: The handler expression parser already references <code>@t</code> as a translations context. This should be the primary consumer API.</li>
</ol>


